<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eleocharis</i> <i>acicularis</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Alopecurus</i> <i>geniculatus</i>, <i>Deschampsia</i> <i>danthonioides</i>, <i>Eleocharis</i> <i>macrostachya</i>, <i>Epilobium</i> <i>pallidum</i>, <i>Epilobium</i> <i>pygmaeum</i>, <i>Eryngium</i> <i>alismifolium</i>, <i>Eryngium</i> <i>castrense</i>, <i>Eryngium</i> <i>mathiasiae</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>arcticus</i>, <i>Lolium</i> <i>perenne</i>, <i>Marsilea</i> <i>vestita</i>, <i>Mimulus</i> <i>guttatus</i>, <i>Muhlenbergia</i> <i>filiformis</i>, <i>Nasturtium</i> <i>officinale</i>, <i>Navarretia</i> <i>intertexta</i>, <i>Navarretia</i> <i>leucocephala</i>, <i>Paspalum</i> <i>dilatatum</i>, <i>Plagiobothrys</i> <i>mollis</i> and <i>Psilocarphus</i> <i>oregonus</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 50 cm; cover is open to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Eleocharis acicularis</i> > 30% relative cover as a codominant to dominant with other wetland herbs in the herbaceous layer (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
		
		<li><i>Eleocharis acicularis, E. bolanderi, E. parishii</i>, or <i>E. quinqueflora</i> dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer (Potter 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Plagiobothrys mollis</i> or <i>Navarretia leucocephala</i> ≥ 20% absolute cover, and <i>E. acicularis</i> usually > 30% cover and co-dominant in the herbaceous layer (S. Smith 1998).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Seasonally flooded channel scours, floodplains, seeps on flats, vernal pools. Soils are usually volcanic and rocky or clayey. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Eleocharis acicularis</i> as an OBL plant </div>
</div>

        
