<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eleocharis acicularis </i>is a cool-season spike rush that attains a height of 15 cm. Its fruits have many ridges and crossbars, and they are weakly 3-sided. This perennial species has a range that includes Eurasia and not only North America but also South America (Smith et al. 2002). The annual or rarely perennial <i>E. bella </i>is often considered a variety of <i>E. acicularis </i>(Hickman 1993).The alliance in California includes stands of <i>E. acicularis </i>co-dominant with <i>Eryngium </i>spp., <i>Navarretia </i>spp.<i>, </i>and <i>Plagiobothrys mollis </i>var. <i>mollis</i>. S. Smith (1998) considered two provisional alliances where <i>E. acicularis </i>is co-dominant with other herbs as early seral disturbance types, the result of long-term grazing and natural disturbances. Klein et al. (2007) found the <i>Eleocharis acicularis </i>alliance as a stable, vernally moist herbaceous type without major disturbances. A related type from alkaline claypan vernal pools in the Solano-Colusa region is the <i>Eleocharis acicularis </i>sub-association of the <i>Downingia insignis-Psilocarphus brevissimus </i>association (Barbour et al. 2007b). <br/>
<br/>
The National Vegetation Classification (NatureServe 2007a) recognized an <i>Eleocharis acicularis </i>alliance in wet meadows of the West, and a <i>Plagiobothrys </i>spp. alliance in vernal pools of Oregon and Washington that includes <i>E. acicularis</i>. Further sampling and analysis of vernal pools and vernally moist meadows in northern California, including stands with <i>E. acicularis, </i>is necessary to identify the relationships of this alliance to other similar wetland alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
