    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Eleocharis acicularis</i> includes cismontane California.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261G). Stands are small, but likely to be widespread throughout the section. S. Smith (1998b) proposed a <i>Plagiobothrys mollis</i> meadow type with high constancy and cover of <i>E. acicularis</i> and <i>Eryngium mathiasiae</i> in floodplain sites on rocky scoured channels and clayey floodplains. <i>P. mollis</i> has a range that includes the northern Sierra Nevada, especially eastside locations. She also proposed a <i>Navarretia</i> meadow type with high cover of related <i>Eleocharis bella</i> and <i>Eryngium alismifolium</i> in silty stream bars and drying vernal pools. We include both of these types in this alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261E). Potter (2005) identified an <i>Eleocharis quinqueflora-Mimulus primuloides</i> association, in which some stands have dominance of <i>E. bella</i> with other spike rushes within the middle to upper elevations of the Sierra Nevada. Although Potter does not split these stands out into different types, we do place some in this alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261F). Klein et al. (2007) recognized <i>Eleocharis acicularis</i> alliance with high constancy of <i>Eryngium castrense, Mimulus guttatus,</i> and <i>Rorippa nasturtium-aquaticum</i> on volcanic seeps and stream banks in Shasta Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261D). Stands in high <i>E. acicularis</i> constancy in the section are similar to those in the Modoc Plateau (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eleocharis acicularis </i>has high erosion control potential (USDA 1993). It appears to occur in season-long grazing areas (S. Smith 1998b); however, <i>E. acicularis </i>is susceptible to damage from overgrazing (Menke et al. 1996). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Associations</h4>
        
            
            <ul class="text">
                
                    <li>Eleocharis acicularis - Eryngium castrense [1]</li>
                
                    <li>Navarretia spp. - (Eleocharis acicularis - Eryngium alismifolium) [2]</li>
                
                    <li>Plagiobothrys mollis - (Eleocharis acicularis - Eryngium mathiasiae) [2]</li>
                
            </ul>
        
    </div>

    
